│ the legacy cost model. This typically happens when the VPlan infrastructure can perform an optimization that the legacy path cannot, leading to different cost      │
│ assessments.                                                                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ The provided reproducer involves a loop with a live-in value (`%add`) that can be constant-folded. The VPlan-based vectorizer is likely performing this constant    │
│ folding, resulting in a lower cost estimate for vectorization compared to the legacy cost model, which doesn't see this optimization. The assertion fails because   │
│ the function `planContainsAdditionalSimplifications` does not account for this specific simplification (constant folding of live-ins).                              │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ To fix this, I need to make `planContainsAdditionalSimplifications` aware of this optimization. The plan is as follows:                                             │
│ 1.  Introduce a flag in the `VPlan` class (defined in `VPlan.h`) to track whether any live-in values were folded into constants during the VPlan's construction.    │
│ I'll add a boolean member `HasFoldedLiveIns` and corresponding getter/setter methods.                                                                               │
│ 2.  In `LoopVectorize.cpp`, locate the call to `VPlanTransforms::foldConstantLiveIns`. This function returns a boolean indicating if it performed any folding. If   │
│ it returns `true`, I will call the new setter to set the flag on the `VPlan` instance.                                                                              │
│ 3.  Finally, in the `planContainsAdditionalSimplifications` function within `LoopVectorize.cpp`, I will add a check for this new flag. If the flag is set for the   │
│ VPlan corresponding to the current vectorization factor, the function will return `true`, correctly signaling that the cost model disagreement is expected and      │
│ justified.                                                                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ This will resolve the assertion failure by explicitly accounting for the simplification that caused the cost models to diverge. I will perform these modifications  │
│ and submit the patch in a single command to ensure the changes are applied before testing.                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                             │
│ sed -i '/VPValue \*getEntryValueFor(const Value \*V) const;/a\                                                                                                      │
│ \                                                                                                                                                                   │
│   /// Flag indicating if any live-ins were folded to constants during\                                                                                              │
│   /// VPlan construction.\                                                                                                                                          │
